Pioglitazone does not lower blood sugar levels directly.

It increases tissue insulin sensitivity, which is generally a positive effect in anyone. It's also used to improve diastolic blood pressure in non-diabetics.

As there's no sign of caloric loss or gain on pioglitazone in study participants it's safe to say that it's not driving people's blood sugar down.

standard dose of pioglitazone is 30mg per day, not to exceed 45mg.
some trans girls do 15mg a day when cutting (to save money/wear and tear on the body) and 30mg a day when gaining. that's up to you.
you also ideally want to gain as fast as possible when in a gain cycle on pio since rapid gain makes your body prefer to make new fat cells (placed in feminine spots with proper female estrogen/testosterone level + the pio) instead of filling old ones (where your male fat cells already exist).
try to stick to healthy, good fats when you do this. trans fats lead directly to visceral fat (which is going to encourage male fat patterning if you're struggling with that). alcohol is bad for this too.
pioglitazone is still the wild west as far as the most effective doses/methods/timing goes for feminization, so ymmv, do your research, etc.
but the standard for virtually guaranteed results either way seems to be 30mg a day.

Rosiglitazone has a lipogenic effect on facial subcutaneous depots.
>"Subcutaneous preadipocytes were isolated from human facial and abdominal skin and cultured in the presence of differentiation factors including rosiglitazone [...] Unexpected superior adipogenic capacity of facial preadipocytes was observed; more facial preadipocytes differentiated in response to rosiglitazone than abdominal preadipocytes and facial preadipocytes retained their ability to differentiate"
source: https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.4161/21623945.2014.955402

However, glitazones, as ligands of the PPARgamma receptors, may have a negative impact on breast growth. Some studies report breast cancer growth inhibition when glitazones like pioglitazone and rosiglitazone are used and activate PPARgamma:
>"Ligands for PPARγ include natural compounds such as fatty acids and their derivatives and synthetic agents such as the antidiabetic drugs rosiglitazone (Avandia) and pioglitazone (Actos) [13]. Although central role of PPAR-γ has been demonstrated in the differentiation of adipose cells, PPARγ has also been shown to regulate the growth, differentiation, and gene expression in number of different cancer cells"

Example would be
>totally identical estrogen/progesterone etc dosing throughout entire trial
>reasonably consistent diet and exercise throughout (whether that's shit diet and no exercise or healthy and exercise, doesn't matter but noting what it was is good info)
>start at weight x, take extensive measurements
>change weight by y over time period t, take extensive measurements
>return to weight x over time period u, take extensive measurements
>introduce pioglitazone dose
>change weight by y in over time period t, take extensive measurements
>compare measurements and note changes between hrt plus weight change (incl. y = 0 if chosen) alone vs hrt plus weight change plus pioglitazone

There are obviously more ways that this could be improved in good ways, but this is accessible to everyone and I wouldn't call someone's data shit for not doing more.

Some basic reading on pio suggests it has a potentially very not good cardiac damage axis particularly in endocrine-female patients (aka, anyone on MtF HRT too). The leg swelling people keep mentioning is fluid buildup from the first stage of congestive heart failure, which pio is known to initiate and potentially exacerbate in some cases.

It is by far the most dangerous DIY thing suggested so far as far as I've seen. It's also entirely possible that the feminization/fillout gains are actually partly influenced by the fluid retention described above, which means they'll dissipate once pio is stopped, or if it potentially kills you. I think I'm gonna skip this one.

Hi all, reporting back on my pre/post Prog measurements, and experiments with Bica to see if that'd stop the androgenic effects I was experiencing. Throughout this time I've been on Finasteride in conjunction with Goserelin. Initially I took Estradiol sublingually, moved to injections before the second set of tests, but I doubt that has much of an effect.
Effects I experienced from Progesterone:
>Massively increased ejaculate
>Libido increase, fuzzy localized euphoric warmth around prostate upon administration
>Heavy sedation effect within 1-2 hours of administration, like taking a sleeping pill
>Increased sweat, body odor more musky/pungent
>Increased oiliness around face, genitals, etc. Exuberation of fungal acne.
>Breast tenderness and growth (subsided after cessation of P4)
On prog:
>T: 22 ng/dL
>DHT: 5 ng/dL
>3A-ADG: 90 ng/dL
Off prog:
>T: 19 ng/dL
>DHT: 9 ng/dL (weird, might've been cause I smoked a cig an hour before the test lol, also could be that Progesterone does inhibit 5ar, not enough testing done to confirm however, not enough $$$)
>3A-ADG: 70 ng/dL (despite serum DHT being higher, this still measured lower, why I say serum DHT isn't representative of peripheral activity. neither is this wholly tbf but it's better than nothing)
Another thing to note is I switched from Subl -> Injections during this time, but I doubt that'd affect things much.

Oh forgot to mention in original post, Prog also caused me to have rock hard erections again...
I started 25mg ED of Bicalutamide, choosing dosage according to the pharmacokinetic parameters available on Wikipedia and my existing measurements of T/DHT. I front-loaded 50mg for a week, then took 25mg ED for a further week to hit steady state. Previously I noticed that it took around 1-2 weeks for the androgenic effects like sweating and BO to ramp up, so I took it for at least two weeks.
Effects were as follows:
>Increased ejaculate for the first few days, went back to normal (either blanks with delayed ejac or tiny dribble) after around 4 days
>Erections weren't rock hard, more soft
>No noticeable libido increase
>No localized fuzzy euphoria in the area of administration/prostate (I think this might've been due to other factors regardless)
>No noticeable increase in sweat or body odor
>No noticeable changes to skin oiliness anywhere, including face. Acne remained the same. If anything, my skin was too dry due to Bica blocking remaining androgens, P4 didn't seem to remedy this.
>Continued heavy sedation effect, noticeable 1-2 hours after administration
>Breast tenderness and swelling, small increase in volume
Was only two weeks as I need to stop to reconvene and convince my Endo to prescribe Bica. If they don't, I'm going full on DIY. Just that it's cheaper for me to pay for 1 appt/yr and get Bica/Prog on the NHS (prepayment cert).
I plan to repeat this soon for a longer period of time to definitely confirm. But it's been positive so far. Other benefits I noticed were that my hair took forever to get ridiculously oily, which was a nice change from having to wash it completely every 3 days.
A weird thing I did notice, was that my sleep quality was better off Prog than on Prog. On Prog I had problems staying asleep, but no problems on only E. This only happened after Prog, not Bica. No idea why, I have some ideas but there's no point in speculating.

It's supposed to be used monthly by cis women as birth control, and . The wikipedia article on that DHPA (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algestone_acetophenide) doesn't seem to mention any blood clotting issues or any other serious side effects, and this article (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12254509/) from 1970(!), though I can't access the full PDF, seems to conclude that it doesn't affect clotting factors if injected once a month in cis women as birth control. This other article (https://sci-hub.ru/10.1007/BF01849664) from 1996 also only showed non-serious side effects or menstrual related side effects. Another article (https://sci-hub.ru/10.1016/0010-7824(94)90002-7) from 1994 mentioned the past studies on the neoplastic effects of that combined contraceptive preparation, mainly breast tumors in dogs and pituitary hyperplasia in rats, but it also mentions another article that puts into question the validity of those animal models how much the effects can be extrapolated for humans.

However, I'm still a bit scared because it's not a widely used progestin in the west, and I'm afraid the only reason there is no clear evidence of serious side effects is because of how it wasn't thoroughly investigated due to it only being used in latin america.

posts.com:
>>29596838
Hydroxyprogesterone Caproate is listed on hrt.coffee and diyhrt, and its effects are known. It's affinity for the progesterone receptor is only 26%, but the higher dosage in every injection compensates it.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydroxyprogesterone_caproate
It is known not to activate the membrane progesterone receptors or the GABAA receptors, only the nuclear progesterone receptors, as opposed to bioidentical progesterone. This means that it doesn't have PR sedative effects of progesterone. I've made a superficial search, and I haven't found strong evidence of breast growth being mediated via mPRs, only nuclear progesterone receptors.

In addition, since it is not a produg, but the caproate form has progestogenic effects directly, and it is not cleaved into the bare 17α-hydroxyprogesterone, this is a form of progestin that does not lead to conversion into androgens, as opposed to progesterone.

I ordered from Otokonoko last month with Kraken, it worked fine.

Basically you plug in your order, see how many dollars you'll need, and buy five dollars extra of USDT on the crypto site. Then you wait three days or however long the withdrawal hold is, place the actual order, and "withdraw" crypto into the address Otokonoko says. It should verify within an hour.

Store the crypto as USDT or whatever the exchange calls dollars, that way they won't lose value and force you to buy extra. Buy from otokonoko with USDT (more convenient, no need to convert) or litecoin (lower transfer fee). When you withdraw check how much the exchange charges in a transfer fee, and _add that to the withdrawal sum_.

>>29612850
Hold off on the prog. You shouldn't be taking prog for the first or second years, and if you decide transition isn't for you, that's money you haven't spent. A mixed vial only stores for about two years anyway, so if you buy three vials of E you'll run out just as they're about to expire, and that's probably a better time to start on prog as well. Prog can stunt boob growth if you start it too early, so ideally you wait until after their growth stops/slow significantly.
Buy the estradiol enanthate. Higher half life means you'll get a smoother curve and less risk of hot flashes etc. Also for travel etc it's pretty nice to be able to go two weeks without needing to shoot up. Consider subq injections instead of into muscle, less chance of hitting a nerve (big pain), and you can use standard insulin syringes for comfort and to save money.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>29613629
>oral has been ineffective to me
>sublingual would be too expensive
Sublingual is cheaper than oral for the same hormone level in your blood. Less estradiol (strong estrogen) gets converted into estrone (weak estrogen) in the liver when you do buccal/sublingual than when you do oral.
3mg is on the lower end of a sublingual dose (I usually see 4mg tossed around), but I know girls who got prescribed 2mg oral who had no changes taking their pills orally, but got good results once they switched to taking the same dose sublingually. 3mg is more even though valerate is a bit weaker, it should be fine.

If money is a problem you should just buy homebrew. Or brew it yourself. You can import estradiol and mix it with hand sanitizer for cheap and easy DIY gel, Reddit has a board for that ("estrogel"), or you could buy MCT oil and estradiol enanthate raws and make injectable (best option).

I don't know about you, but I'd much prefer taking a tablet sublingually twice a day, or injecting once a week, over having to slather my balls in estrogel twice a day. It just seems so much more convenient.

Goal of the thread: At the end of the day, try to write a journal entry listing positive experiences you had throughout the day, cute things you've seen, things that were nice, you get the idea.

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

>single+mutli-variable calculus
>linear algebra
>differential equations
>real analysis
>measure theory
>functional analysis

If you study full time, then technically you can make it in a year, but functional analysis is at least mid level or upper level of grad level courses, since it has grad level course as a pre-requisite.
I think you also want

>linear+non-linear optimization
>topology
>differential geometry
